    "concept": "IB2: Awfulizing — Definition",
    "chapter": "Chapter 4: The Seven Irrational Beliefs",
    "content": "Awfulizing is when we take unpleasantness and make it more unpleasant than it is; we exaggerate the event or situation to an extreme degree. The dictionary defines awful as simply unpleasant, but the way Ellis used it—as the basis for 'awfulizing'—is closer to what we may call 'catastrophizing.' In this sense, indicating the thought that something is not just unpleasant, but so much worse than unpleasant that it can't be measured. When we awfulize, we are perceiving something as being off the scale of suffering. This belief that anything can be completely 100% negative is irrational and damaging. There are, however, emotional consequences. Every time you tell yourself, 'This is as bad as it gets,' you are creating an irrational belief.",
