  {
    "concept": "IB2: Awfulizing — Three Options for Disputing",
    "chapter": "Chapter 4: The Seven Irrational Beliefs",
    "content": "There are three ways to dispute Awfulizing. You don't need all three, one should be enough, but in case one doesn't work you have options.\n\nOPTION 1: AWFUL AS AN ATTRIBUTE\nWe often use awful as an attribute—ascribing an inherent characteristic to something that doesn't actually possess it. It's subjective—an opinion. There is nothing that inherently possesses awful, so this is automatically false. If you asked twenty people in an art museum what they thought of a painting, some would love it and others would say it was awful. You could say to all the second group, 'Put your finger on the awfulness in the painting.' It can't be done. Awful doesn't actually exist in the painting—it is something that exists in the mind! When you realize you have created the concept of awful in your mind, you can then dispute the irrational belief that you have no choice but to feel disturbed. If you created the disturbance, you can get rid of it!\n\nOPTION 2: AWFUL AS AN EXAGGERATION\nThe second way to dispute awful is to put it on a scale of unpleasantness from 0% to 100%. Zero percent would mean that nothing was unpleasant and 100% would be the worst thing that could ever happen to you or others in this lifetime. Where does the thing you are calling awful fall? Visualizing a scale helps us see that things could always be worse. When we use 'awful' to describe our belief about a situation we don't like, we are saying it isn't even on a scale of unpleasantness—it's off the scale! It's 110% or 400% which, of course, is impossible. Something could always be worse, therefore nothing can ever be entirely awful.\n\nOPTION 3: AWFUL AS A SHOULD\nThe third way to disprove awful is to realize when we are using awful as a Should: to say that it is so unpleasant that it shouldn't exist! When you call something awful, you are saying that because you don't like it, it shouldn't exist! This is egocentric thinking and leads to suffering, because no matter how much we would like something not to exist, it exists because all the conditions are there for it to exist. Reality does not adjust itself to our likes and dislikes.",
    "type": "framework",
    "references": "IB2: Awfulizing — Definition; Disputing — Definition; IB4: Shoulds, Musts, and Demands; Resistance to Reality (Chapter 3)"
  },

